AGI&nbsp; - "radical changes that are necessary" to "be at the height of today's and tomorrow's world" which "has caught surprise" the European Union with "other regions that no longer respect the rules" and would like the EU "permanently dependent on them". The former President of the ECB and former Italian Prime Minister, Mario Draghi, takes advantage of the High Level Conference on the European Pillar of Social Rights, in Le Hulpe outside Brussels, to give some anticipation of the report on Competitiveness that is drafting for the European Commission and will present to the European Council after the June elections.
&nbsp;
Draghi lacks an 'industrial deal' that can respond in particular to the challenges posed by China and the United States. The first "mira to agguantate and internalize all parts of the supply chain of green and advanced technologies and is guaranteeing access to the necessary resources". With a "hot expansion of the offer that is leading to a significant excess of capacity in multiple sectors and threatening to weaken our industries". The United States, on their part, "will use a large-scale industrial policy to attract high-value national manufacturing capabilities within its borders - including that of European companies - while using protectionism to exclude competitors and deploy its geopolitical power to reorient and protect supply chains. The European framework outlined by Draghi is alarming.
&nbsp;
"We lack a strategy on how to keep pace in an increasingly ruthless race for leadership in new technologies. Today we invest less in digital and advanced technologies than the United States and China, even for defense, and we have only four global European technological players among the top 50 worldwide. There is no strategy on how to protect our traditional industries from unequal global play ground caused by asymmetries in regulations, subsidies and commercial policies. An example is represented by the energy-intensive industries," he explained.
&nbsp;
"In other regions, these industries not only have to cope with lower energy costs, but must also face a lower regulatory burden and, in some cases, receive massive subsidies that directly threaten the ability of European companies to compete. Without strategically designed and coordinated political actions, it is logical that some of our industries will reduce production capacity or move outside the EU," he warned the former issue of the ECB.
&nbsp;
"And we lack a strategy to ensure we have the resources and inputs we need to achieve our ambitions without increasing our dependencies. We rightly have an ambitious climate agenda in Europe and ambitious targets for electric vehicles. But in a world where our rivals control many of the resources we need, this agenda must be combined with a plan to protect our supply chain, from critical minerals to batteries to charging infrastructure."
&nbsp;
The reasons outlined by Draghi indicate that Europe remained firm and not at the pace of changed times. "Our response was limited because our organization, decision-making and funding are designed for yesterday's world: pre-Covid, pre-Ukraine, pre-conflagration in the Middle East, before the return of rivalry among great powers. But we need a suitable EU for the world today and tomorrow. So what I propose in the report which the President of the Commission has asked me to prepare is a radical change, because that is what we need."
&nbsp;
Ultimately, "we will have to make a transformation throughout the European economy. We must be able to count on decarbonized and independent energy systems; an integrated and adequate EU-based defence system; national manufacturing in the most innovative and rapidly growing sectors; and a leadership position in technological and digital innovation close to our production base." In his report, Draghi identifies ten macrosectors of the European economy on which to intervene with specific reforms and tools for each.
&nbsp;
"However, in our analysis three common threads emerge for political interventions," he points out. And they are: scalability, supply of public goods and supply of resources. "In the defence sector, for example, lack of scale is hindering the development of European industrial capacity, a problem recognised in the recent European Strategy for the Defence Industry." Another example is telecommunications. Another example in which we are not exploiting the scale is that of telecommunications.
&nbsp;
"We have a market of about 450 million consumers in the EU, but per capita investment is half the US and we are lagging behind in the spread of 5G and fiber. One of the reasons for this gap is that in Europe we have 34 groups of mobile networks - and this is a prudent estimate, in reality we have many more - that often operate on a national scale, against three in the United States and four in China. To produce more investment, we must further rationalize and harmonize telecommunications regulations between Member States and support, not hinder, consolidation." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"The second line concerns the provision of public goods. Where there are investments from which we all benefit, but that no country can achieve alone, we have good reasons to act together, otherwise we will not provide adequate results compared to our needs: We will not provide satisfactory results in terms of climate, for example in defence, and in other sectors." Finally, resources. "Once we identify these public assets, we must also give us the means to finance them. The public sector has an important role to play and I have already talked about how we can better use the EU's joint loan capacity, especially in areas such as defence. But most of the investment gap will have to be covered by private investments. The EU has very high private savings, but they are mostly channelled into bank deposits and do not end up financing growth as they could in a larger capital market. This is why the Union's progress in capital markets is an indispensable part of the overall strategy for competitiveness."
&nbsp;
For Draghi "we cannot afford the luxury of delaying answers to all these important questions until the next amendment of the Treaty. In order to ensure consistency between the different political instruments, we should be able to develop a new strategic tool for coordinating economic policies. And if we have to find out that this is not feasible, in specific cases, we should be ready to consider proceeding with a subset of Member States. For example, enhanced cooperation in the form of a 28th scheme could be a way for the Union of Capital Markets to mobilize investment. But as a rule, I believe that the political cohesion of our Union requires that we act together - possibly always. And we must be aware that political cohesion is today threatened by changes in the rest of the world."
&nbsp;
"Restoring our competitiveness is not something we can achieve on our own, or only by beating each other - the former Italian premier has concluded. "It requires us to act as a European Union in a way never before. Our rivals are preceding us because they can act as a single country with a single strategy and align behind it all the necessary tools and policies. If we want to match them, we will need a renewed partnership between the Member States, a redefinition of our Union which is no less ambitious than what the Founding Fathers did 70 years ago with the creation of the European Coal and Steel Community." &nbsp;
&nbsp;

